recordings.rmk: I am not sure this particular vocalization is known by many.  At least Cornell University's extensive library of sounds does not have it to the best of my knowledge.  It is a male reacting to a furry wind cover over a microphone in my 'bird garden'.  The bluebird and his mate feed frequently on a tube of mealworms right next to the microphone, and he would not come in.  I have never heard this before in this species.  Note the thrush-like quality of the call note.

recordings.rmk:
One of the birds from XC171662.  Several segments from the same recording session (breaks at 2:31, 3:21, 8:26).  The bird moved between perches in open oak savanna. Segments correspond to different perches. Around 3:46, a second bird flies into the tree and there is audible wing noise as they chase eachother around the tree. After the intruder is chased off, the song becomes louder and more agitated, and you can hear the second bird countersinging for a little while.

Recorded with Sennheiser ME66 and Olympus LS-10S. Temperature fairly warm but a bit overcast, still significant snow cover on the ground. Filtered low frequencies for traffic hum.

recordings.rmk: Heard singing from the top of a deciduous tree in open woodland area. Adult male song. Bird could be seen and sported the blue back and head and very rusty breast of adult male Eastern Bluebirds, there is another male Eastern Bluebird singing in the background who was also seen. The bird paused a lot and would be silent for some minutes and then sing several phrases again for some minutes. There is a silent part in the recording to indicate when there was a pause in the field before the individual started to sing again, in which I took another separate recording, but I merged them together in Audacity since the songs are from the same bird.

recordings.loc: Hassayampa River Preserve, Wickenburg, Maricopa County, Arizona
recordings.rmk: Heard the bird calling outside my office window at the visitor center and got 20-second recording. By the time I ran outside with the camera it was gone. Recorded with iPhone SE, amplification, high pass filter, and noise reduction used in Audacity. Casual in Maricopa County (this would be only 3rd or 4th record). Presumably of the nominate S.s. sialis population, which is migratory (the 'Azure' bluebird of southeastern AZ and the Sierra Madre Occidental is believed to be sedentary). Western Bluebirds have also been around lately, so it may be associating with their flocks visiting the mistletoe clumps in the areas.
